In small-scale societies, storage is often carried out at the household level; however, as complexity, specialization, and interdependence increase, elites are able to extract and control surplus grains (
 
  50
 ). Presumably, these grains are redistributed to farmers that contribute them in times of famine; however, this is not always the case. In societies based around household structure, subterranean storage associated with the house is often used to avoid freeloading (
 
  51
 ).
